{{refimprove|date=February 2017}} {{infobox person |name=Rabbi Levi Yitzchak Schneerson |image=[[File:Rebbi Levi Yitzchak Schneerson.jpg|150px|Rabbi Levi Yitzchak Schneerson]] |birth_date=April 28, 1878 |birth_place=Podrovnah, Russia |death_date=August 9, 1944 |death_place=[[Almaty|Almaty, Kazakhstan]] |spouse=[[Chana Schneerson]] |known_for=''Likkutei Levi Yitzchak'' on [[Kabbalah]] and [[Chabad philosophy]] |occupation=Chief Rabbi of [[Dnepropetrovsk|Yekatrinoslav]], Russia |children= *Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel Schneerson]] *Yisroel Aryeh Leib Schneerson *Dovber Schneerson }}[[File:Stamp of Kazakhstan 565.jpg|thumb|Chabad synagogue in Almaty, depicted on a Kazakh stamp]] '''Levi Yitzchak Schneerson''', (1878-1944), was a [[Chabad|Chabad-Lubavitch]] [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] [[rabbi]] in [[Dnipro|Yekatrinoslav]], [[Ukraine]]. He was the father of the seventh and last [[Chabad-Lubavitch]] [[Rebbe]], Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel Schneerson]].
==Biography== Rabbi Levi Yitzchak was born on the 18th day of Nissan, 5638 (1878) in the town of Podrovnah (near [[Gomel]]) to Rabbi Baruch Schneur and Zelda Rachel Schneerson. His great-great grandfather was the third Chabad Rebbe, Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel Schneersohn]] of [[Lubavitch]].
In 1900, Levi Yitzchak married [[Chana Schneerson|Chana Yanovski]], whose father, Rabbi {{Interlanguage link multi|Meir Shlomo|he|3=מאיר שלמה ינובסקי}}, was the Rabbi of the Ukrainian city of [[Mykolaiv|Nikolaiev]]. In 1902, their eldest son, Menachem Mendel was born. He was later to become the [[Rebbe]] of [[Chabad-Lubavitch|Lubavitch]].
Schneerson lived in Nikolaiev until 1909, when he was appointed to serve as the Rabbi of [[Dnepropetrovsk|Yekatrinoslav]]. In 1939 he was arrested by the [[Bolsheviks|communist]] regime for his fearless stance against the Party's efforts to eradicate Jewish learning and practice in the [[Soviet Union]], and particularly for distributing [[Matzah]] to the Jews of Yekatrinoslav.<ref>[http://www.jweekly.com/article/full/5490/is-matzah-the-key-to-soviet-jews-survival/ "Is Matzah the Key to Soviet Jews Survival."] Jweekly.com.</ref> After more than a year of torture and interrogations in [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]]'s prisons, he was sentenced to exile to a remote village Chiali in [[Kazakhstan]]. Shortly before his death, Levi Yitzchak was able to move to [[Almaty]], where he was warmly welcomed by the small [[Jews in Kazakhstan|Lubavitcher community]]. There he died on the 20th of Av, 5704 (1944).<ref>[http://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/2283906/jewish/Rabbi-Levi-Yitzchak-Schneerson.htm "Rabbi Levi Yitzchak Schneerson (1878–1944) The life and legacy of the Rebbe’s father"] chabad.org.</ref> Rabbi Levi Yitzchak was buried at a cemetery in Almaty. A Chabad Lubavitch synagogue named in his honour has been built near his gravesite.
Schneerson was a distinguished [[Kabbalah|Kabbalist]]. Some of his writings have been published in a five volume set under the name ''Likkutei Levi Yitschok''. Most of it, however, was burned or confiscated by the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] authorities, and has yet to be returned to the Chabad movement.
==Further reading== * Gottlieb, Naftali Tzvi. Trans. Lesches, Elchonon. "Rabbi, Mystic and Leader - the Life and Times of Rabbi Levi Yitzchak Schneerson" (Kehot Publication Society; 2008) 253 pages * Schneerson, Chana. Trans. Tilles, Yerachmiel. "A Mother in Israel - the Life and Memoirs of Rebbetzin Chana Schneerson" (Kehot Publication Society; 1985, 2003) 226 pages
==External links== *[http://www.loebtree.com/tsemah.html#lys Family Tree with Rabbi Levi Yitzchak Schneerson] *[http://www.chabad.kz/contentManagment//rabiLeviCategory.asp?articleCategoryID=7&tableName=rabi_levi_category_table&lang=english Rabbi Levi Yitzchak's biography on Chabad-Lubavitch Kazakhstan] *[https://www.chabad.org/article.asp?aid=2658278 Select teachings of Rabbi Levi Yitzchak Schneerson translated into English] *[https://www.chabad.org/therebbe/article_cdo/aid/2658208/jewish/His-Life-and-Times.htm Life and times of Rabbi Levi Yitzchak Schneerson on Chabad.org]
